The construction of the South Stream pipeline in Bulgaria, the launch of one of the largest European energy projects, the Gazprom executive said.
"Today's event is a milestone: the construction work on the Bulgarian section of South Stream gas pipeline, the largest and most important project in Europe, have begun," said the executive board chairman of Gazprom, Alexei Miller, on Thursday in a statement.
The project is a key element for the energy security of the entire European continent.
South Stream is intended to ensure greater diversity in Russia's export routes across Europe.
A contract dispute between Gazprom and its counterparts in Ukraine, where the bulk of Russian gas to Europe, provide an increased risk for conventional routes, such as official.
Miller said that the direct connection to Bulgaria, a member of the European Union, means that the geopolitical risks associated with transit countries are "off forever."
Bulgarian consumers receive gas from South Stream at special rates, if the project goes into operation in 2015.
According to Gazprom to begin the construction work in other countries downstream on the planned route at the end of the year.
The pipeline is designed to have an annual capacity of 62.3 billion cubic meters of gas.
